<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1540,1963]" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">
This species was known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[650,748,1684,1710]" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[765,836,1684,1711]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[182,1384,240,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[173,1415,179,1883]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. South-east Asian Sesiini. 1–2. Lamellisphecia minwangi Arita &amp; Kallies, sp. nov., male, holotype, China. 1. dorsal aspect. 2. ventral aspect. 3–4. Lamellisphecia champaensis, Vietnam. 3. male, holotype. 4. male. 5. Lamellisphecia wiangensis, male, holotype, Thailand. 6. Lamellisphecia haematinea, male, holotype, Thailand. 7. Aegerosphecia fumoptera, male, holotype, Vietnam. 8. A. fumoptera, female, paratype, Vietnam." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3568934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3568934/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). We can now report two additional specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,249,1720,1746]" name="Vietnam" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, collected at the type locality, and two specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[877,935,1721,1747]" name="Laos" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">Laos</collectingCountry>
. The two additional specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1341,1436,1720,1746]" name="Vietnam" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
differ from the 
<typeStatus box="[321,419,1756,1782]" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">holotype</typeStatus>
by the more extensive yellow-orange marking of the abdomen, with tergite 3 being reddish orange and tergite 4 yellow-orange. The two specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[857,911,1793,1819]" name="Laos" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">Laos</collectingCountry>
differ from the ones from 
<collectingCountry box="[1220,1315,1792,1818]" name="Vietnam" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
by having tergite 5 completely yellow-orange in addition to tergites 3 and 4 (
<figureCitation box="[886,955,1828,1855]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[182,1384,240,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[173,1415,179,1883]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. South-east Asian Sesiini. 1–2. Lamellisphecia minwangi Arita &amp; Kallies, sp. nov., male, holotype, China. 1. dorsal aspect. 2. ventral aspect. 3–4. Lamellisphecia champaensis, Vietnam. 3. male, holotype. 4. male. 5. Lamellisphecia wiangensis, male, holotype, Thailand. 6. Lamellisphecia haematinea, male, holotype, Thailand. 7. Aegerosphecia fumoptera, male, holotype, Vietnam. 8. A. fumoptera, female, paratype, Vietnam." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3568934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3568934/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Although this gives them a quite different appearance, they do not show additional distinctive features. We therefore believe that these specimens belong to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kallies &amp; Arita" authorityYear="2004" box="[151,327,1901,1927]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Lamellisphecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="480" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="champaensis">
<emphasis box="[151,327,1901,1927]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="480">L. champaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as and suggest that the extent of yellow-orange markings on the abdomen alone is not suitable to separate different species.
</paragraph>
